Let $x,$ $y,$ and $z$ denote $\tfrac{a}{b},$ $\tfrac{a}{c},$ and $\tfrac{b}{c},$ respectively. Since $a,$ $b,$ and $c$ are positive, we can express them as multiples of another variable, say, $k$. Hence,
  \begin{align*}
  a &= xk \\
  b &= yk \\
  c &= zk
\end{align*}
Clearly, if any of $x,$ $y,$ and $z$ equal $1,$ the unknown $k$ can be easily found; however, I like to keep it separate at all times. Because $a,$ $b,$ $c$ are positive, all of $x,$ $y,$ and $z$ must also be positive. Also notice that: </think> \begin{align*}
  \frac{a+b}{c} &= \frac{(x+1)k}{z k} = \frac{x+z}{z} \\
  \frac{b+c}{a} &= \frac{(y+z)k}{xk} = \frac{y+z}{x} \\
  \frac{c+a}{b} &= \frac{(z+x)k}{yk} = \frac{x+z}{y}
\end{align*}Hence,
  \[\frac{(a+b)(a+c)(b+c)}{abc} = \frac{(x+1)(y+1)(z+1)}{xyz} = \left(\frac{x}{x}+\frac{x}{y}\right)\left(\frac{y}{x}+\frac{y}{y}\right)\left(\frac{z}{x}+\frac{z}{y}\right).\] <answer> minimizing this after expanding gives $9,$ which occurs when $a=b=c$.
